# **PREFACE**

This thesis began not in a library or a university but in front of a screen, in the early hours of the morning, with an image overlay that would not resolve in any way that made conventional sense.

For several years I had been working simultaneously on two projects that the academic world treats as entirely separate: a kinematic analysis of the Madrid Codex I — Leonardo da Vinci's engineering masterwork — and a doctoral investigation into the production methodology of the Turin Shroud. The Madrid project was proceeding folio by folio, building a systems interpretation of the codex as a unified mechanical treatise rather than a collection of isolated sketches. The Shroud project was building an evidential case for a production method consistent with fifteenth-century optical and chemical technology.

The connection between the two became apparent on the day I overlaid the Vitruvian Man on the Shroud body at correct scale. The proportions were not approximately aligned. They were precisely aligned — face, shoulders, navel, feet — at every major anatomical landmark simultaneously. I spent several weeks checking and rechecking the measurement. The scalar factor connecting the two objects is 7.1. It is derivable from Fibonacci compound proportion. It is not approximate. It is arithmetic.

From that single mathematical observation, the thesis assembled itself over the following months. The Armenian letters — already known to Leonardo scholars but treated as peripheral curiosities — suddenly became central. The geological backgrounds of the paintings became a travel diary. The Islamic arabesque in the Academy emblem became a cultural signature. The mirror writing became a directional encoding. The recto-verso structure of the Madrid Codex I became the same structural law that governs the Shroud itself. Everything that had seemed peripheral became central once the Vitruvian scalar was established.

I am an independent scholar without institutional affiliation. I have no university behind me, no departmental funding, no research assistant, and significant physical challenges that make the mechanics of academic writing difficult. What I have is thirty years of obsessive original observation across disciplines that academic convention keeps separate, and a unifying instinct that refused to accept that Leonardo's mechanical engineering and his sacred art were not expressions of the same underlying system.

This thesis is the record of that instinct proven.

All intellectual property, all original methodologies, and all analytical frameworks described herein are solely my own. Copyright is vested exclusively in Richard Steven Vallance © 2026. Any convergence with positions reached independently by other scholars — including the recent emergence of scholarly interest in Leonardo's Islamic connections — does not diminish the originality of this thesis's unified argument, which has not previously been made in this form.

