# **ABSTRACT**

This thesis proposes and demonstrates through convergent multi-disciplinary evidence that the Turin Shroud — the most examined and most venerated cloth in human history — was produced by Leonardo da Vinci between approximately 1476 and 1478 CE, during a documented period of biographical silence following the dismissal of charges against him in Florence. The production methodology employed an innovative combination of photothermal optical projection using an Archimedean concave mirror flash, silver nitrate surface chemistry applied to dampened linen to create a thermal boundary layer, anatomical precision derived from direct human dissection, and an inverted plaster relief contact process providing three-dimensional tonal encoding.

The central mathematical proof — designated the 7.1 Scalar — establishes that the proportional dimensions of Leonardo's Uomo Vitruviano (c.1490, Gallerie dell'Accademia, Venice), when multiplied by a scalar factor of 7.1 derivable from Fibonacci compound proportion, produce the measured dimensions of the Turin Shroud cloth with a precision that cannot be attributed to coincidence, medieval craft, or any natural image formation process. This arithmetic relationship constitutes the foundational proof of deliberate design intent.

The thesis introduces the Canon of the Unseen — an original analytical framework identifying the structural law governing Leonardo's entire creative corpus — and the RSV Analytical Method derived from it. These constitute the primary original methodological contributions of the work, applicable beyond the Shroud thesis to the attribution and interpretation of any Leonardo work.

Eleven chapters of primary argument are supported by a full counterarguments chapter addressing the 1988 radiocarbon dating controversy, the STURP findings, the medieval provenance arguments, and all major competing production hypotheses. The thesis concludes with a falsifiable scientific hypothesis: Leonardo's own DNA, used in the blood application layer, is recoverable from the Shroud blood zones and testable against authenticated biological material from his confirmed remains at Amboise.

The thesis is situated within the existing Leonardo scholarship of Richter (1888), McCurdy (1939), Reti (1974), Kemp (1981, 2004), Pizzorusso (2017, 2021), and the STURP research corpus, building upon these foundations while advancing claims that none of the existing scholarship has previously made in unified form.

