# **AUTHOR****'****S NOTE ON METHOD AND SOURCES**

This thesis makes claims across multiple disciplines — art history, optical physics, textile chemistry, geology, documentary history, biblical studies, and forensic science. The author is an independent scholar without institutional affiliation. This is not a weakness of the argument but a condition of its possibility.

The convergent proof model employed throughout proceeds as follows: multiple independent lines of evidence from multiple disciplines are assembled such that each line of evidence is independently established and independently significant, and their convergence on a single conclusion constitutes a proof stronger than any single-discipline argument could provide. No expert in any single contributing discipline can dismiss the whole by reference to their own specialism alone.

### ***Primary Sources***

All Leonardo primary source quotations are drawn from Richter (1888) as the primary scholarly edition, with McCurdy (1939) and Baring (1906) used for supplementary passages. The Madrid Codex I transcriptions presented in this thesis are the author's own working translations from the BNE digital facsimile, constituting original translation work in the absence of any freely available complete English translation of Madrid I. The Reti 1974 edition, where accessible, has been used for verification.

### ***The Missing Years — A Note***

Chapter One includes an extended discussion of the biographical gap of 1476-1478 and the subsequent period 1481-1482. The evidence assembled for this chapter draws on: the absence of documentary record (confirmed across multiple independent biographical sources); the authenticated Armenian letters in the Codex Atlanticus; the geological transition in Leonardo's painting backgrounds; the cultural evidence of Islamic influence in his work; and the dated note entries of the Madrid Codex I that bracket the gap from both sides.

The conclusion that Leonardo was physically present in the Armenian Highlands and Ottoman-adjacent territories during the gap period is the author's original interpretation of convergent evidence already in the public record. It is framed as the most probable hypothesis consistent with all available evidence rather than a demonstrated certainty.

### ***On Citations and Footnotes***

All direct quotations are cited to their primary source. Where a quotation is sourced from a secondary edition of a primary text (e.g., Richter's translation of Leonardo), both the Leonardo source and the edition are cited. Footnotes provide source citations, explanatory notes, and cross-references to other chapters. The bibliography lists all sources cited in the body text together with relevant background reading.

# **CHAPTER ONE**

***The Core Hypothesis***

*The Last and Greatest Work*

## **1.1 Statement of the Hypothesis**

**Leonardo da Vinci did not forge a relic. He completed one.**

The Turin Shroud — the linen cloth preserved in the Cathedral of Saint John the Baptist in Turin, venerated by hundreds of millions of people across five centuries as the authentic burial cloth of Jesus Christ — is the terminal work of a guild lineage that began before Leonardo, passed through him, and ended with him. It is the physical proof of a unified theory of art, science, theology, and proportion that Leonardo da Vinci spent his entire working life developing, and which no other work in his corpus expresses as completely.

Every painting Leonardo produced, every engineering diagram he drew, every anatomical study he completed, every philosophical observation he committed to mirror script in his private notebooks — all of them point toward this object. The Shroud is where the trajectories of his thought, his technical capability, his Islamic and classical learning, and his Neoplatonic theology converged into a single physical expression that no other craftsman in the history of Western civilisation could have produced.

This thesis does not propose a mystery. It proposes a solution. The answer to the oldest unsolved question in Christian relic history — what is the Turin Shroud, who made it, when, and how — is documentable, testable, and in several cases already confirmed by evidence that has been in the public record for decades but has not previously been assembled into a unified argument of this form.

The Shroud is a full-scale photothermal projection of the human body produced by Leonardo da Vinci in approximately 1476-1478 CE using optical, chemical, and mechanical methods consistent with his documented knowledge. It was placed on genuinely ancient Palestinian or Egyptian linen sourced through Mamluk trading networks during a documented gap in his biographical record. It is proportioned to a scalar multiple of 7.1× his own Vitruvian module, encoded with his own facial geometry, authenticated by a blood application using his own biological material, and stored in a Fibonacci fold sequence that connects the cloth's dimensions to the same mathematical system as its image.

It is the greatest work of art ever produced. It has been misidentified for five centuries because it was designed to be misidentified — by the only man in history with the intelligence and the technical range to design it that way.

**1. **The attribution hypothesis has been raised previously in popular literature — most notably by Lynn Picknett and Clive Prince in Turin Shroud: In Whose Image? (1994) — but without the mathematical proof, the production methodology, or the unified systems analysis presented here. The 7.1 Scalar, the Canon of the Unseen, and the RSV Analytical Method constitute original scholarly contributions not previously published.

**2. **For the primary physical description of the Shroud, see STURP (Shroud of Turin Research Project), 'A Summary of STURP's Conclusions,' 1981. Available at www.shroud.com/78conclu.htm.

## **1.2 Why This Thesis Is Possible Now**

The question of Shroud authorship has attracted scholarly and popular attention continuously since the object's first documented public exhibition at Lirey, France in approximately 1357. In the twentieth century alone it has been the subject of direct scientific investigation by STURP (1978), radiocarbon dating by three independent laboratories (1988), and hundreds of peer-reviewed publications across disciplines ranging from textile analysis to forensic blood chemistry to digital photogrammetry.

Yet the authorship question has remained open. The present thesis makes claims that were not previously makeable for the following specific reasons.

First, the digital availability of the Madrid Codex I through the Biblioteca Nacional de España's interactive viewer (leonardo.bne.es) makes it possible for independent scholars to engage directly with Leonardo's primary engineering text in a form that was previously available only to institutional researchers with physical access to the manuscript collections in Madrid. The folio-by-folio analysis that forms the basis of the Codex project component of this thesis — including the identification of seepage alignment methodology, the central shaft doctrine, and the recto-verso structural logic — was conducted entirely from this digital resource.

Second, the Gutenberg and Wikisource digitisation of the complete Leonardo notebook corpus in English translation makes the full Richter and McCurdy editions searchable and cross-referenceable in a way that was previously impractical for an independent scholar. The identification of the Armenian letters, the Quranic citation, and the dated entries that bracket the biographical gap was made possible by searchable access to these resources.

Third, digital image overlay and analysis methodology — demonstrated in the visual evidence portfolio of this thesis and developed by the author over several years of independent investigation — makes it possible to produce and verify the proportional alignment proofs that the 7.1 Scalar argument requires. These overlays are not interpretive approximations. They are precise geometric alignments verifiable by any researcher using the same public domain images and the same methodology.

Fourth, the development of ancient DNA extraction and analysis methodology since the 1990s has advanced to the point where the DNA endgame hypothesis of Chapter Ten is a realistic scientific proposal rather than a speculative aspiration. The identification of Leonardo's probable biological remains at Amboise and the active work of the Vincian Committee on DNA extraction from authenticated Leonardo material means that the cross-referencing test proposed in Chapter Ten is proximate rather than distant.

These four conditions together constitute the specific technological and methodological context that makes the present thesis possible in 2026 and was not available to earlier investigators.

**3. **The Biblioteca Nacional de España's interactive Leonardo Codex Madrid viewer is accessible at https://leonardo.bne.es. The viewer provides high-resolution folio images with transcription and Spanish translation. No complete English translation of Madrid Codex I is freely available.

**4. **The Richter edition (Project Gutenberg eBook #5000) provides the complete notebook text in English. The Armenian letter drafts are discussed in Richter's preface and reproduced in section XIV of Volume II.

## **1.3 The Structure of the Argument**

The thesis proceeds in three movements corresponding to framework, evidence, and synthesis.

The first movement — Chapters Two through Five — establishes the theoretical and historical framework. Chapter Two traces the guild lineage through which Leonardo inherited the Shroud problem, arguing that the tradition had been working toward this object for four generations before Leonardo provided the convergent capabilities to complete it. Chapter Three addresses the fraud question directly and situates Leonardo's position within Renaissance Neoplatonism, demonstrating that the Shroud encodes not mere deception but a coherent theological argument about the relationship between divine proportion and incarnate form. Chapter Four establishes the Vitruvian Man as Leonardo's personal geometric operating system — not a study of ideal proportion but the master module governing his entire corpus across every medium. Chapter Five analyses Leonardo's language doctrine from the Trattato della Pittura and demonstrates that the Shroud is the physical fulfilment of that doctrine — the image that needs no translation.

The second movement — Chapters Six through Nine — presents the primary evidence in four domains. Chapter Six provides the mathematical proof through the 7.1 Scalar, establishing the arithmetic relationship between the Vitruvian module and the Shroud dimensions and deriving the scalar from Fibonacci compound proportion. Chapter Seven analyses the two-layer construction of the Shroud — the photothermal image layer and the deliberate blood application layer — demonstrating through STURP's own findings that these are separate, sequential operations consistent with a controlled two-session production process. Chapter Eight reconstructs the full production methodology: the inverted plaster relief providing contact geometry, the two-half asymmetric projection explaining the bilateral hand anomaly, the glass slide lightbox providing facial registration, and the Archimedes mirror flash providing the instantaneous high-intensity energy required for superficial fibril oxidation. Chapter Nine assembles the provenance: the Armenian letters, the Ottoman network documentation, the geological backgrounds as travel diary, and the dated Madrid Codex I entries of 1493 and 1497 that bracket the biographical gap from both sides.

The third movement — Chapters Ten through Twelve — completes the argument with the DNA endgame hypothesis, the final synthesis, and the full counterarguments chapter. Chapter Ten presents the falsifiable scientific hypothesis that Leonardo's own DNA is recoverable from the Shroud blood zones. Chapter Eleven synthesises all preceding chapters into the unified statement of Figura Ultima. Chapter Twelve addresses every significant counterargument in the existing literature, demonstrating in each case either the technical inadequacy of the counterargument or its dependence on evidence now known to be compromised.

