## **1.5 A Note on Method**

This thesis makes claims across multiple disciplines simultaneously. The convergent proof model is not a weakness but a structural feature: it means that the argument cannot be dismissed by any single specialism because no single specialism contains all the evidence. The mathematician can evaluate the 7.1 Scalar independently of the art historian's reading of the backgrounds. The forensic chemist can evaluate the STURP evidence independently of the documentary historian's reading of the Armenian letters. The geologist can evaluate the mountain background analysis independently of the physicist's assessment of the mirror flash mechanism. Each domain of evidence is independently established and independently significant. Their convergence is not constructed — it is the consequence of all the independent lines pointing in the same direction.

The thesis explicitly distinguishes between proven claims, strongly supported hypotheses, and speculative proposals. The 7.1 Scalar is proven — it is arithmetic. The two-layer construction is proven — it is confirmed by STURP. The Armenian letters are authenticated — Richter's judgment stands. The geological backgrounds are strongly supported — consistent with Taurus Mountain geology and inconsistent with any Italian landscape. The Archimedes mirror flash is a strongly supported hypothesis — it satisfies all physical constraints uniquely. The DNA hypothesis is speculative until tested — but it is falsifiable, which is the scientific standard that matters.

The reader is invited throughout to apply this distinction. The argument does not require every claim to be at the same level of certainty. The mathematical proof of Chapter Six stands independently of the DNA hypothesis of Chapter Ten. The attribution is established by the convergent evidence of Chapters Six through Nine without requiring the DNA confirmation — which is proposed as the definitive verification rather than as the necessary proof.

**5. **Leonardo wrote: 'Those who are enamoured of practice without science are like a pilot who goes into a ship without rudder or compass and never has any certainty where he is going.' Notebooks (Richter 1888), Vol. I, §19.

**6. **On the methodology of convergent proof in historical investigation, see R. G. Collingwood, The Idea of History (Oxford, 1946), Part V; and Carlo Ginzburg, 'Morelli, Freud and Sherlock Holmes,' History Workshop 9 (1980): 5-36.

## **1.6 The Missing Years: Biographical Context and the Eastern Journey**

The missing years are not a minor biographical footnote. They are the pivot of the entire thesis. Understanding them precisely is the condition for understanding why the Shroud is where it is, what it is, and who made it.

Leonardo da Vinci was born 15 April 1452 in Vinci, the illegitimate son of Ser Piero da Vinci, a Florentine notary, and Caterina, a peasant woman of uncertain origin — scholars have increasingly argued she may have been a baptised slave from Muslim lands, of whom there was a sizable population in Florence at the time. This biological and cultural origin is not irrelevant to the thesis: a man whose mother may have come from the Islamic world would have had a natural conduit to the Islamic intellectual and cultural traditions he demonstrably absorbed.

He entered Verrocchio's workshop approximately 1466 and was still registered there in 1476, when two legal documents confirm his presence. On 9 April 1476 an anonymous denunciation was placed in the tamburo — the complaint box of the Florentine Officers of the Night — accusing Leonardo and three other young men of sodomy with a known male prostitute named Jacopo Saltarelli. The case was filed for reinvestigation on 7 June 1476, but no witnesses came forward and the charges were ultimately dismissed for lack of evidence.

From the date of the dismissal until January 1478, when Leonardo notes in his notebooks that he has begun two Virgin Marys, there is no authenticated document, dated notebook entry, commission record, tax record, guild registration, or eyewitness account that places Leonardo at any specific location doing any specific thing. This is the primary gap.

The conventional biographical assumption — that Leonardo remained in Florence during this period, perhaps in his own workshop — is an assumption made in the absence of evidence rather than an inference from evidence. The assumption is possible. It is also implausible for a man of Leonardo's documented habits, who dated his notebook entries to specific days and recorded observations of remarkable precision throughout his working life. A man who on 28 September 1497 would record the name, parentage, age, and musical achievement of a nine-year-old Turkish boy playing lute in Milan does not produce twenty months of complete documentary silence in Florence unless he is not in Florence.

### ***What the Record Shows in the Gap***

The key documentary evidence for what Leonardo was actually doing in 1476-1478 falls into three categories.

First, the Armenian letters in the Codex Atlanticus. These authenticated documents in Leonardo's own hand — draft letters addressed to the Devatdar of Syria, a senior Mamluk official designated as lieutenant of the sacred Sultan of Babylon (Egypt) — describe Leonardo's physical presence in the mountains of Armenia, his observation of a devastating earthquake in the Taurus Mountains, his citation of Surah 99 of the Quran to name what he had witnessed, and his activities in carrying out a commission for the unnamed Oriental lord who sent him there.

Jean Paul Richter, the principal scholarly editor of the Leonardo notebooks, examined these documents carefully and concluded that despite the extraordinary nature of their content — and despite the fact that no existing Leonardo biography had previously accounted for any eastern travel — the handwriting, spelling, language, and accompanying architectural sketches were all unambiguously Leonardo's own work. He was there. He wrote these letters. The question is only when.

The dating of the Armenian letters cannot be precisely established — they are undated draft fragments rather than sent correspondence. But three independent lines of evidence point to the gap period as the most probable window. First, the biographical silence is the only extended period in Leonardo's documented life where an absence of several months would leave no contradicting record. Second, the geological backgrounds of the paintings he produced immediately after the gap period — the two Marian paintings of 1478, the Adoration of the Magi underdrawing of 1481-1482 — show transitional geology inconsistent with Tuscany, as if he is beginning to encode eastern geological memories in Italian sacred subjects. Third, the Sultan Kait Bey of Egypt made a documented inspection tour of the northern territories of his empire in autumn 1477 — precisely the Taurus Mountains and Tigris-Euphrates corridor that Leonardo describes in the Armenian letters — providing a specific diplomatic-commercial event to which Leonardo's commission could be attached.

Second, the re-emergence note of late 1478. When Leonardo resurfaces in the documentary record he notes — on a sheet in the Uffizi Gallery that also bears the date and the year — that he has begun two Virgin Marys. Not one. Two simultaneously. This is the first dated note after the gap. A man beginning his public artistic career again after a period of absence chooses as his first recorded act two paired images of the Madonna — one encoding the cross the child cannot yet see, one encoding the blood-red carnation of the Passion. These are the two layers of the Shroud encoded in paired paintings in the moment of his return.

Third, the lute player entry of 28 September 1497. This dated note in the Madrid Codex I is the most humanly revealing document in the entire corpus. In the middle of his most systematic mechanical engineering work, Leonardo stops to record a precise personal observation: Tadeo, son of Nicholaio del Turcho — Nicholas of the Turk — had just turned nine years old on the eve of Saint Michael's Day, was in Milan, played lute, and was judged one of the finest players in all Italy. He noted the father's name: of the Turk. The Ottoman network that runs through the Armenian letters runs through the lute player entry twenty years later. Leonardo moved in circles that included Ottoman-connected individuals in Milan in 1497 as naturally as he had moved in Mamluk-connected networks in Armenia in 1477.

### ***The Post-Gap Period 1481-1482***

A second period of partial documentary silence runs from approximately mid-1481 to early 1482. Leonardo had received two major Florentine commissions — the Chapel of Saint Bernard altarpiece (January 1478) and the Adoration of the Magi for the monks of San Donato a Scopeto (March 1481). Neither was completed. Both were abandoned when Leonardo departed Florence for Milan.

The Adoration of the Magi underdrawing — the most complex preparatory work Leonardo ever produced for an unfinished painting — shows in its architectural background a geological and structural complexity that has puzzled art historians. The ruined classical architecture in the background contains geometric and spatial relationships that art historian Martin Kemp and others have noted as unusually sophisticated for a background element. The thesis proposes that this background encodes the technical architecture of the Shroud production apparatus — the lightbox, the relief setup, the mirror geometry — disguised as classical ruins.

Whether or not this specific encoding is accepted, the abandonment of both major Florentine commissions at the same moment — without completing either, apparently suddenly, in favour of an unsolicited departure for Milan — is consistent with a man who has another project to complete before entering the most public phase of his career.

The thesis proposes that the Shroud was substantially complete before Leonardo left for Milan. The final stages — the blood application, the fold geometry, the transfer to Savoy custody through the Medici-court network — were accomplished in the 1481-1482 window before departure. When Leonardo arrived at the Sforza court in Milan in 1482, the Shroud was already in circulation. The next phase of his life — the great Milanese works — was the consequence rather than the context of the Shroud's creation.

**7. **On Leonardo's mother's possible origin, see Renzo Cianchi, 'Leonardo's Mother,' Raccolta Vinciana 21 (1982), and Walter Isaacson, Leonardo da Vinci (2017), ch. 1.

**8. **The sodomy charge and dismissal: archival documents discussed in Michael Rocke, Forbidden Friendships: Homosexuality and Male Culture in Renaissance Florence (Oxford, 1996), pp. 100-101.

**9. **Jean Paul Richter on the Armenian letters: The Notebooks of Leonardo da Vinci (1888), Vol. II, Section XXI introduction, pp. 282-283: 'But on close examination no one can doubt that these documents, with the accompanying sketches, are the work of Leonardo's own hand. Not merely is the character of the handwriting his, but the spelling and the language are his also.'

